<subSubSection id="2489D58DFFFB7E62FCCB609239B0EEA2" pageId="8" pageNumber="693" type="description">
<paragraph id="6C2C8606FFFB7E62FCCB60923E97EE39" blockId="8.[813,1421,644,1059]" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">
<emphasis id="5EE75A14FFFB7E62FCCB6092398AE886" bold="true" box="[813,974,644,668]" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">Identification.</emphasis>
The SVL is up to 
<quantity id="AB6B2BE3FFFB7E62FB4660933EB9E886" box="[1184,1277,645,669]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="693" unit="mm" value="180.0">180 mm</quantity>
. The body is large, with the dorsum greenish overall, but turning yellow after the first monsoon shower. We did not see any bright-yellow individuals with neon blue vocal sacs and instead only say a few individuals with some yellowish coloration on the flanks and dorsum. We noted that some frogs retain their yellowness throughout the breeding season. The feet are fully webbed. This frog is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="AB93FD85FFFB7E62FCAE61B73E1EE9A2" authority="(Jerdon, 1853)" baseAuthorityName="Jerdon" baseAuthorityYear="1853" box="[840,1114,928,952]" class="Amphibia" family="Dicroglossidae" genus="Hoplobatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="8" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis id="5EE75A14FFFB7E62FCAE61B739FFE9A2" box="[840,955,929,952]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">H. crassus</emphasis>
(Jerdon, 1853)
</taxonomicName>
; however, 
<taxonomicName id="AB93FD85FFFB7E62FB2B61B73F7AE9A2" baseAuthorityName="Jerdon" baseAuthorityYear="1853" box="[1229,1342,929,952]" class="Amphibia" family="Dicroglossidae" genus="Hoplobatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="8" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis id="5EE75A14FFFB7E62FB2B61B73F7AE9A2" box="[1229,1342,929,952]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">H. crassus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species with a very limited range, and has oval spots on the lower limbs rather than the stripes of 
<taxonomicName id="AB93FD85FFFB7E62FB3761FE3F16E9E5" baseAuthorityName="Daudin" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[1233,1362,1000,1023]" class="Amphibia" family="Dicroglossidae" genus="Hoplobatrachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="8" pageNumber="693" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tigerinus">
<emphasis id="5EE75A14FFFB7E62FB3761FE3F16E9E5" box="[1233,1362,1000,1023]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">H. tigerinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The call is wheezing, nasal, and growl-like.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6C2C8606FFFB7E62FCCB662039B0EEA2" blockId="8.[813,1420,1078,1208]" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">
<emphasis id="5EE75A14FFFB7E62FCCB662039C8EE54" bold="true" box="[813,908,1078,1102]" pageId="8" pageNumber="693">Habitat.</emphasis>
This species was seen in semi-aquatic habitats and on the edges of perennial lakes and other water bodies. It is also known from secondary forests lined with acacia plantations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
